    {
      "page_num": 5,
      "text_blocks": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "SESSION OBJECTIVES",
          "bbox": [
            166.33999633789062,
            87.31198120117188,
            388.2459716796875,
            119.37598419189453
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "At this point in the course, we are about to move from explicit symbolic tools to \nprobabilistic models and, later, to neural architectures such as transformers. \nBefore making that transition, it is important to understand how raw text \nbecomes something a system can operate on in the first place.",
          "bbox": [
            109.08000183105469,
            188.239990234375,
            602.1199951171875,
            251.83999633789062
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Regular expressions address this layer. They do not attempt to model meaning, \nintention, or context. Instead, they impose structure on text, making it possible \nto detect formats, enforce constraints, and extract specific elements. This is why \nthey appear here, immediately before classifiers and representation-learning \nmodels: they solve problems that must be addressed before learning can even \nbegin.",
          "bbox": [
            109.08000183105469,
            273.0799865722656,
            602.1254272460938,
            369.1000061035156
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "This unit focuses on turning text into data. The central question is how \nunstructured language can be transformed into something that can be counted, \ncompared, weighted, and eventually classified.",
          "bbox": [
            109.08000183105469,
            390.2200012207031,
            602.1199951171875,
            437.6199951171875
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "The progression is conceptual as well as technical. Raw text is first structured \nthrough pattern detection, then summarized through counting and weighting, \nand only later fed into statistical models. Regular expressions represent the first \nstep in this progression. They are the point at which text stops being prose and \nstarts becoming an object of computation.",
          "bbox": [
            109.08000183105469,
            458.8900146484375,
            602.1199951171875,
            538.6900024414062
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "102\nAI: Natural Language Processing",
          "bbox": [
            29.591999053955078,
            611.9760131835938,
            1122.480712890625,
            626.3759765625
          ]
        }
      ],
      "images": [
        {
          "type": "image",
