    {
      "page_num": 6,
      "text_blocks": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "WHAT ARE REGULAR EXPRESSIONS?",
          "bbox": [
            586.1799926757812,
            101.99002075195312,
            973.634521484375,
            134.03001403808594
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Regular expressions are a formal language for specifying patterns in text. \nOperationally, they define text search strings. Formally, a regular expression can \nbe understood as an algebraic notation for characterizing a set of strings.",
          "bbox": [
            535.1300048828125,
            209.07000732421875,
            1028.1700439453125,
            260.07000732421875
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Originally introduced by Stephen Kleene in the context of automata theory, \nregular expressions describe families of strings using a finite set of symbols and \noperators. They are not arbitrary formulas, but constrained expressions whose \nstructure corresponds to regular languages.",
          "bbox": [
            535.1300048828125,
            283.09197998046875,
            1028.1754150390625,
            352.1300048828125
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "For example, the following regular expression describes a broad class of URLs:",
          "bbox": [
            535.1300048828125,
            375.04998779296875,
            1008.1600341796875,
            390.04998779296875
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "\\b(?:(?:https?|ftp):\\/\\/)?(?:www\\.)?[a-zA-Z0-9-]+(?:\\.[a-zA-",
          "bbox": [
            600.77001953125,
            413.0719909667969,
            959.1773681640625,
            428.09600830078125
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Z]{2,})(?:\\/[^\\s?#]*)?(?:\\?[^\\s#]*)?(?:#[^\\s]*)?\\b",
          "bbox": [
            633.6500244140625,
            431.1199951171875,
            926.094970703125,
            446.1199951171875
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "This \npattern \nmatches \nstrings \nsuch \nas \nhttps://www.example.com \nor \nhttp://example.co.uk/path/to/page",
          "bbox": [
            535.1300048828125,
            469.1600036621094,
            1028.1700439453125,
            502.1600036621094
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "The expression does not “understand” what a URL is. It specifies a structural \npattern that valid URLs typically satisfy.",
          "bbox": [
            535.1300048828125,
            525.0800170898438,
            1028.1700439453125,
            558.083984375
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "103\nAI: Natural Language Processing",
          "bbox": [
            29.591999053955078,
            611.9760131835938,
            1122.480712890625,
            626.3759765625
          ]
        }
      ],
      "images": [
        {
          "type": "image",
          "path": "output/images/page6_img0.png",
          "width": 212,
          "height": 238
        },
        {
          "type": "image",
          "path": "output/images/page6_img1.jpeg",
          "width": 766,
          "height": 1024
        }
      ],
      "tables": []
    },
    {
      "page_num": 7,
      "text_blocks": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "REGULAR EXPRESSIONS IN THE NLP PIPELINE",
          "bbox": [
            535.0999755859375,
            160.8699951171875,
            1014.0646362304688,
            192.9099884033203
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "In a realistic NLP pipeline, regular expressions appear early. They are used \nduring data cleaning, preprocessing, and feature preparation, long before any \nclassifier or neural model is applied.",
          "bbox": [
            535.1300048828125,
            240.44000244140625,
            1028.1700439453125,
            291.4460144042969
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Consider a raw input string such as \"<p>Pay €1,249.50 now</p>\"",
          "bbox": [
            535.1300048828125,
            314.5,
            928.4049682617188,
            329.5
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Before tokenization or vectorization makes sense, the markup needs to be \nremoved, and the relevant value needs to be identified. A regular expression \ncan remove tags and extract the monetary amount deterministically.",
          "bbox": [
            535.1300048828125,
            352.4200134277344,
            1028.1700439453125,
            403.41998291015625
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "In Python, this typically looks like searching or substituting patterns using the re \nmodule, long before any model sees the text.",
          "bbox": [
            535.1300048828125,
            426.489990234375,
            1028.1700439453125,
            459.489990234375
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "This role aligns naturally with the broader pipeline structure used throughout \nthe course, where preprocessing precedes feature extraction and modelling.",
          "bbox": [
            535.1300048828125,
            482.5299987792969,
            1028.1700439453125,
            515.530029296875
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "104\nAI: Natural Language Processing",
          "bbox": [
            29.591999053955078,
            611.9760131835938,
            1122.480712890625,
            626.3759765625
          ]
        }
      ],
      "images": [
        {
          "type": "image",
          "path": "output/images/page7_img0.png",
          "width": 212,
          "height": 238
        },
        {
          "type": "image",
          "path": "output/images/page7_img1.jpeg",
          "width": 766,
          "height": 1024
        }
      ],
      "tables": []
    },
    {
      "page_num": 8,
      "text_blocks": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "WHAT PROBLEM REGULAR EXPRESSIONS SOLVE",
          "bbox": [
            117.12000274658203,
            174.21200561523438,
            584.7980346679688,
            204.2360076904297
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Regular expressions answer structural questions about text. They tell us \nwhether a string matches a required format, where in the text a pattern \nappears, and which substrings satisfy that pattern.",
          "bbox": [
            109.08000183105469,
            238.81198120117188,
            602.1254272460938,
            289.8500061035156
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Take the sentence",
          "bbox": [
            109.08000183105469,
            312.8900146484375,
            221.92999267578125,
            327.8900146484375
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "\"Contact me.home@ie.edu before 12/03/2026.\"",
          "bbox": [
            206.5399932861328,
            350.80999755859375,
            501.3050231933594,
            365.80999755859375
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "From a structural perspective, we may want to detect whether an email address \nappears, whether a date appears, and to extract both. A regular expression can \ndetect the email pattern and return the exact substring that matches it. In \nPython, this typically involves a call such as re.search or re.findall, which \nreturns the location and content of the match.",
          "bbox": [
            109.08000183105469,
            388.8800048828125,
            602.1199951171875,
            475.8800048828125
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "None of this requires understanding what the email refers to or what the date \nmeans. These are pattern-level operations, and that is precisely their scope.",
          "bbox": [
            109.08000183105469,
            498.9019775390625,
            602.1254272460938,
            531.9400024414062
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "105\nAI: Natural Language Processing",
          "bbox": [
            29.591999053955078,
            611.9760131835938,
            1122.480712890625,
            626.3759765625
          ]
        }
      ],
      "images": [
        {
          "type": "image",
          "path": "output/images/page8_img0.png",
          "width": 212,
          "height": 238
        },
        {
          "type": "image",
          "path": "output/images/page8_img1.jpeg",
          "width": 796,
          "height": 1024
        }
      ],
      "tables": []
    },
    {
      "page_num": 9,
      "text_blocks": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "WHY REGULAR EXPRESSIONS STILL MATTER",
          "bbox": [
            503.1099853515625,
            97.18997192382812,
            960.4947509765625,
            129.22996520996094
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Modern NLP systems rely heavily on transformers, but transformers do not \neliminate the need for structure. They presuppose it.",
          "bbox": [
            535.1300048828125,
            180.55999755859375,
            1028.1700439453125,
            213.5659942626953
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Transformers are trained on large volumes of already normalized text. In \npractice, before passing data to such models, we often need to remove \nboilerplate, normalize spacing, discard malformed inputs, or extract fields that \nshould not be treated as free text.",
          "bbox": [
            535.1300048828125,
            236.6199951171875,
            1028.1700439453125,
            305.6199951171875
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "For example, if a dataset contains log entries, identifiers, or prices embedded in \ntext, it is rarely sensible to let a model infer their structure from scratch. A short \nregular expression applied in Python can enforce consistency and prevent entire \nclasses of errors. In this sense, regular expressions protect the pipeline at its \nboundaries, where reliability and transparency matter most.",
          "bbox": [
            535.1300048828125,
            328.5220031738281,
            1028.1754150390625,
            415.57000732421875
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "In practice, regular expressions are used to clean text by removing markup and \nnoise, to extract fields such as dates, prices, or identifiers, to normalize \ninconsistent formatting, and to filter out malformed inputs.",
          "bbox": [
            535.1300048828125,
            438.6099853515625,
            1028.1754150390625,
            489.6300048828125
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "These operations are often invisible when models perform well, but they are \nfoundational. Many failures attributed to models are in fact failures of \npreprocessing.",
          "bbox": [
            535.1300048828125,
            512.6699829101562,
            1028.1700439453125,
            563.6699829101562
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "106\nAI: Natural Language Processing",
          "bbox": [
            29.591999053955078,
