    {
      "page_num": 10,
      "text_blocks": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "THE LIMITS OF REGULAR EXPRESSIONS",
          "bbox": [
            63.57600021362305,
            99.0999755859375,
            530.2471313476562,
            135.0999755859375
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Regular expressions cannot interpret meaning, resolve ambiguity, or capture long-range dependencies. From a regular-expression \nperspective, the word “bank” in “the bank approved the loan” and in “the river bank overflowed” is identical. This limitation motivates the \nintroduction of statistical models and neural representations later in the course.",
          "bbox": [
            124.01000213623047,
            193.92999267578125,
            1031.6669921875,
            248.2899932861328
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Regular expressions are not abandoned because they are weak or outdated. They are set aside because the nature of the problem changes.",
          "bbox": [
            124.01000213623047,
            271.57000732421875,
            1027.761962890625,
            287.5299987792969
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "As long as the task is to detect formats, enforce constraints, or extract explicitly defined patterns, regular expressions are often the best \npossible tool. They are transparent, deterministic, and efficient.",
          "bbox": [
            124.01000213623047,
            310.7099914550781,
            1031.6669921875,
            345.8699951171875
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "They become inadequate when variation itself becomes meaningful. When two strings differ in wording but express the same intent, or \nwhen the meaning of a word depends on context, explicit rules cease to scale. At that point, learning from data becomes not only \nconvenient but necessary.",
          "bbox": [
            124.01000213623047,
            369.1499938964844,
            1031.6669921875,
            423.510009765625
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Regular expressions define what can be solved without uncertainty. Classifiers and transformers are introduced precisely to handle what \nremains once rules have been exhausted.",
          "bbox": [
            128.86000061035156,
            472.0899963378906,
            1030.2769775390625,
            507.25
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "107\nAI: Natural Language Processing",
          "bbox": [
            29.591999053955078,
            611.9760131835938,
            1122.480712890625,
            626.3759765625
          ]
        }
      ],
      "images": [
        {
          "type": "image",
          "path": "output/images/page10_img0.png",
          "width": 212,
          "height": 238
        }
      ],
      "tables": []
    },
    {
      "page_num": 11,
      "text_blocks": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "HOW REGULAR EXPRESSIONS SEE TEXT",
          "bbox": [
            63.57600021362305,
            99.0999755859375,
            524.9527587890625,
            135.0999755859375
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Regular expressions treat text as a sequence of characters. They operate on letters, digits, punctuation, and whitespace, without access to \nwords, syntax, or meaning.",
          "bbox": [
            124.01000213623047,
            193.92999267578125,
            1031.6669921875,
            229.0900115966797
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "At their core, regular expressions combine a small number of simple mechanisms into expressive patterns.",
          "bbox": [
            124.01000213623047,
            252.3699951171875,
            815.7669067382812,
            268.3299865722656
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "•\nLiteral characters match themselves, wildcards match any character, and character classes define sets such as uppercase letters or digits. \nQuantifiers specify how many times a pattern may repeat, and anchors restrict where a match may occur within a string.",
          "bbox": [
            124.01000213623047,
            288.9944763183594,
            1031.6724853515625,
            326.66998291015625
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "•\nAnchors control where patterns apply, and word boundaries prevent partial matches inside longer strings.",
          "bbox": [
            124.01000213623047,
            347.4762268066406,
            834.2469482421875,
            365.9100036621094
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "•\nGroups allow parts of a pattern to be isolated and reused. Through grouping, regular expressions transform unstructured text into \nstructured data that can be extracted, stored, or processed further.",
          "bbox": [
            124.01000213623047,
            386.7162170410156,
            1031.6669921875,
            424.3499755859375
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "By default, regular expressions match as much text as possible. This greedy behaviour can lead to unexpected results when delimiters \nrepeat or when multiple matches are possible.",
          "bbox": [
            127.68000030517578,
            470.9419860839844,
            1029.1124267578125,
            506.1399841308594
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "108\nAI: Natural Language Processing",
          "bbox": [
            29.591999053955078,
            611.9760131835938,
            1122.480712890625,
            626.3759765625
          ]
        }
