    {
      "page_num": 13,
      "text_blocks": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "SPECIAL CHARACTER CLASSES AND ESCAPES",
          "bbox": [
            63.57600021362305,
            60.56201934814453,
            591.3460693359375,
            96.58601379394531
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Character classes like \\d, \\w, and \\s are shortcuts for common sets of characters, while their uppercase counterparts (\\D, \\W, \\S) \nrepresent their complements. Some escapes, such as \\b, \\A, and \\Z, do not match characters at all but rather positions in the string. \nUnderstanding the difference between character matches and positional matches is essential for writing correct and predictable regular \nexpressions.",
          "bbox": [
            97.63200378417969,
            149.92532348632812,
            985.5923461914062,
            225.5600128173828
          ]
        },
        {
