    {
      "page_num": 14,
      "text_blocks": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "LOOKAROUNDS",
          "bbox": [
            63.57600021362305,
            67.88202667236328,
            247.51406860351562,
            103.90602111816406
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Lookarounds are a special class of regular expression constructs that allow a pattern to test its immediate context without actually \nconsuming any characters. Instead of matching text, they match positions in the string. This makes them particularly useful when we \nwant to enforce local constraints on what may appear before or after a match, while keeping the extracted substring clean and \nunchanged.",
          "bbox": [
            108.0,
            142.17999267578125,
            1000.4269409179688,
            215.74000549316406
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "For example, a lookahead can ensure that a number is followed by a percentage sign without including the sign in the match, and a \nlookbehind can ensure that a number is preceded by a currency symbol without capturing that symbol. Because lookarounds do not \nadvance the matching cursor, they are best understood as contextual tests rather than matching operations, and they are often used in \nNLP preprocessing when precise extraction is needed without altering surrounding text.",
          "bbox": [
            108.0,
            239.00198364257812,
            1000.432373046875,
            312.6099853515625
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "111\nAI: Natural Language Processing",
          "bbox": [
            29.591999053955078,
            611.9760131835938,
            1122.480712890625,
            626.3759765625
          ]
        }
